6 partner; and
7 WHEREAS, the robust U.S.-Taiwan trade and investment partnership
8 provides a solid foundation for a mutually beneficial bilateral
9 trade agreement to spur job creation, expand the global market, and
10 secure international, democratic supply chains; and
11 WHEREAS, Taiwan is a pivotal force for stability in the Indo-
12 pacific that amplifies the values of democracy, peace, and
13 prosperity by partnering with like-minded countries through
14 integrated diplomacy to address global challenges; and
15 WHEREAS, Taiwanese officials and civil society groups partner
16 with the U.S. on a range of issues to promote our common values of
17 freedom, democracy, and human rights; and
18 WHEREAS, since 1980, Oklahoma and Taiwan have maintained a
19 sister-state relationship and enjoy particularly close economic
20 ties; Oklahoma exported over $46 million in goods to Taiwan in 2024;
21 and the establishment of an Oklahoma Trade and Investment Office in
22 Taiwan could enhance the participation of small and medium-sized
23 enterprises in trade and investment; and
